    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">A multi-cloud discovery framework based on compostable cost estimation &amp; monitoring</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">W, Bibin</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">A multi-cloud discovery framework<br />cost estimation &amp; monitoring</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">1-May-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Srm University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">P6195</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Scientific computing in the clouds has been one of the most prominent research areas in the field of cloud computing. Traditional scientific computing applications are executed in high complex tightly coupled distributed systems that are difficult to setup and maintain. These systems are not flexible and require a massive amount of configuration task during any change of computation. Cloud computing solves this problem by leaving the low level maintenance to the cloud provider side and allowing the client to concentrate on his computing task. This provided the reason for the shifting of scientific computing applications to the cloud. Clouds also provided flexibility, transparency, reduction in maintenance tasks etc at an increased level when compared to that of traditional distributed systems. Moreover the cost estimation factor in clouds provided a major drawback because of the lacking of an efficient mechanism to estimate the computing cost of a cloud. Various types of cloud computing services utilize varied types of resources that cause a corresponding variation in the computing cost.
Current cloud providers lack a mechanism to monitor the change in configuration to attract the client who are residing in other cloud platforms. This project implements an effective mechanism to dynamically discover the clouds based on their capacity to execute the computing application and a composable cost estimation mechanism for efficient calculation of the computing cost based on the computing service and an event based model for the monitoring of configuration changes in various clouds and then based on the configuration change shifting the application to more efficient clouds. Shifting the application to efficient cloud leads to a decrease in the capital expenditure and also a more efficient methodology of execution that reduces the execution time of the process. The project makes use of existing java based distributed computing capabilities at the maximum for an easy implementation process and paves way for easy upgrade and maintenance</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/17530">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/17530</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/17024">CSE-2013</a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
